    icon: "Search",
    component: "RegexTester",
    longDescription:
      "Regex Tester is for the moment you need to test regular expressions with live match highlighting, flag toggles, and match position list—without an install, an account, or a risky upload. Hosted playgrounds retain samples, and a full IDE is overkill for one payload. A local, deterministic fix is usually enough.\n\nCI failed on a config blob and you want a trustworthy browser check before the next push. A narrow local tool beats guessing in chat.\n\nRegex Tester does one job clearly: test regular expressions with live match highlighting, flag toggles, and match position list. Under the hood it uses the native JavaScript RegExp engine with live match feedback. In practice you enter your regex pattern in the pattern field (between the / delimiters); then toggle the g, i, m, s flag buttons to set regex flags; then paste your test string in the 'Test string' textarea; then matches are highlighted in yellow and listed below with their positions. There is no mandatory upload to ToolBrigade for the core transform. Latency tracks your device and the size of the input, not a distant worker queue.\n\nHere is how people actually use it day to day. You are drafting under NDA and refuse to drop the text or file into an account-walled converter. A client portal rejects the original, so you normalize the file with Regex Tester and upload again. During QA you reproduce an issue locally, run Regex Tester on the sample, and attach the clean output to the ticket. A teammate sends messy input, and Regex Tester turns it into something you can share or ship in one pass.\n\nA few gotchas trip people up. JSON is stricter than JavaScript object literals: trailing commas and single quotes will fail JSON.parse. Base64 often needs padding restored; JWT uses Base64URL, which is not the same alphabet as standard Base64. Percent-encoding is not interchangeable with Base64—mixing them breaks query strings and tokens.\n\nPeople looking for regex tester online free, regex tester without uploading, regex tester in browser no signup, or a free alternative to desktop regex tester software are usually stuck on this exact chore. Regex Tester answers that intent with a narrow, explainable workflow—not a junk drawer of unrelated features.\n\nPrivacy is intentional. Regex Tester runs in your browser on your device, and you do not need an account for the core workflow. Close the tab when you are done; your input is not kept as a ToolBrigade processing archive.\n\nIf a result looks surprising, shrink the sample until the failure is obvious, adjust one setting, then scale back up. That habit is faster than changing five controls at once. Keep the original nearby until you have visually confirmed the export in the destination app or pipeline.\n\nIf a result looks surprising, shrink the sample until the failure is obvious, adjust one setting, then scale back up. That habit is faster than changing five controls at once. Keep the original nearby until you have visually confirmed the export in the destination app or pipeline.\n\nIf a result looks surprising, shrink the sample until the failure is obvious, adjust one setting, then scale back up. That habit is faster than changing five controls at once. Keep the original nearby until you have visually confirmed the export in the destination app or pipeline.",
